item.title: Iran Says It Launched First Military Satellite
item.description: Iran’s Revolutionary Guard said it launched its first military satellite into space, a move American officials have warned could advance Tehran’s missile capabilities, amid renewed tensions with the U.S.

item.title: Argentina Doesn't Make Foreign Debt Payments in Restructuring Standoff
item.description: Argentina said it didn’t make foreign debt payments coming due on Wednesday—starting a countdown to a possible default next month unless authorities and bondholders can restructure tens of billions of dollars in sovereign debt.

item.title: Amazon Deforestation Speeds Up as Coronavirus Hinders Enforcement
item.description: With hundreds of environmental enforcement agents sidelined by the pandemic, deforestation in Brazil’s Amazon has increased to its fastest pace in years—and the season when clearing typically accelerates hasn’t even begun.

item.title: Pakistani Authorities Seek Reinstatement of Death Penalty in Killing of Wall Street Journal Reporter
item.description: Pakistani authorities asked the country’s highest court to reimpose the death penalty for a British national accused of kidnapping and killing Wall Street Journal reporter Daniel Pearl, after a lower court had overturned the 18-year-old murder conviction earlier this month.

item.title: Migrant Workers Set to Send Less Money Home, World Bank Says
item.description: The money—a critical source of support for the developing world—is projected to fall by about 20% this year as the coronavirus crisis hits global economies, the World Bank says.

item.title: Millions of Europeans Are on Paid Leave. Governments Are Picking Up the Tab.
item.description: At least 18 million European workers have been idled over the past month, as the coronavirus pandemic cuts a widening swath through job markets and prompts governments to spend hundreds of billions of dollars to support laid-off workers.
